nodes.name: Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard
nodes.description: The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) v4.0.1 is a comprehensive global security standard developed by the PCI Security Standards Council to protect cardholder data and reduce payment fraud.

nodes.name: PCI DSS v4.0.1
nodes.description: A framework of specifications, tools, measurements and support resources to help organizations ensure the safe handling of cardholder data at every step. Published June 11, 2024 as a refinement to v4.0, providing clarifications and corrections to improve implementation and understanding. Mandatory compliance for all organizations handling payment cards by March 31, 2025.
nodes.definition: The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard v4.0.1 - the current industry security standard for protecting cardholder data.
nodes.key_features: 12 core requirements unchanged; 64 total requirements including new sub-requirements; Customized approach available; Risk-based controls; Expanded MFA requirements; Enhanced third-party management

nodes.name: PCI DSS v4.0
nodes.description: Released March 2022 as major update to v3.2.1. Introduces 64 new requirements, defined and customized approaches, risk-based controls, and expanded scope for cloud services and APIs. Version 4.0 was retired December 31, 2024, replaced by v4.0.1.
nodes.definition: The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard v4.0 - updated version introducing new security controls and flexible compliance approaches.
nodes.key_features: 64 new requirements; Two implementation approaches (defined and customized); Risk-based flexibility; Cloud and API security; Enhanced authentication; Phased compliance deadlines

nodes.name: GDPR
nodes.description: Regulation (EU) 2016/679 enacted May 25, 2018. Comprehensive framework protecting fundamental rights and freedoms of natural persons with regard to the processing of personal data. Applies to any organization processing personal data of EU residents regardless of organization location. Enforced by national data protection authorities.
nodes.definition: General Data Protection Regulation (EU) 2016/679 - comprehensive EU regulation governing data protection and privacy for all organizations processing personal data of EU residents.
nodes.applicable_to: Organizations with EU customers;EU-based organizations;Data processors;Data controllers;Service providers handling EU resident data
nodes.key_features: 99 Articles; 173 Recitals; Right to erasure; Data portability; Explicit consent requirements; Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA); Data Protection Officer requirements for certain organizations; Breach notification within 72 hours

nodes.owner: International Organization for Standardization (ISO); International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC)
nodes.name: ISO 27001:2022
nodes.description: International standard specifying requirements for an information security management system (ISMS). Provides a systematic approach to managing sensitive company information to keep it secure through people, processes and IT systems. Updated 2022 with 93 controls (reduced from 114 in 2013), reorganized into 4 themes: Organizational, People, Physical, Technological. Focuses on risk assessment and treatment.
nodes.definition: International Standard ISO/IEC 27001:2022 for Information Security Management Systems (ISMS) - framework for establishing and maintaining comprehensive information security management.
nodes.applicable_to: Any organization (manufacturing, service, public, private);Organizations seeking information security certification;Organizations with sensitive information assets
nodes.key_features: 93 controls in 4 themes; Risk-based approach; Applies to any size organization; Can be combined with PCI DSS; Clause-based structure (Clauses 4-10); Certification available through auditors

nodes.owner: International Organization for Standardization (ISO); International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC)
nodes.name: ISO 27002:2022
nodes.description: Provides detailed implementation guidance, practices, and considerations for each of the 93 ISO 27001 Annex A controls. Does not mandate implementation of any specific controls but guides best practices for each. Companion standard to ISO 27001 for detailed control implementation.
nodes.definition: ISO/IEC 27002:2022 - Code of practice providing implementation guidance for ISO 27001 information security controls.
nodes.applicable_to: Organizations implementing ISO 27001;Organizations seeking guidance on specific controls;Security teams defining control implementations
nodes.key_features: Detailed implementation guidance for all 93 controls; Control selection rationale; Control objectives; Control implementation considerations; Measurement and metrics guidance

nodes.owner: American Institute of Certified Public Accountants (AICPA)
nodes.name: SOC 2
nodes.description: Framework developed by AICPA for service organizations to demonstrate effectiveness of controls over security, availability, confidentiality, and privacy of customer data. Provides assurance to customers and regulators. Available in Type I (design of controls) and Type II (operating effectiveness) audit formats.
nodes.definition: Service Organization Control 2 - framework for assessing and reporting on the effectiveness of controls implemented by service providers.
nodes.applicable_to: Service Providers;Payment processors;Cloud service providers;SaaS companies;Hosting providers;Data center operators;Security service providers
nodes.key_features: Two audit types: Type I (controls are suitably designed) and Type II (controls operate effectively); Trust Service Criteria; Annual audits; Specific to service organizations

nodes.owner: US Department of Health and Human Services (HHS)
nodes.name: HIPAA
nodes.description: US federal law enacted 1996, revised 2003 (HITECH Act). Requires healthcare providers, health plans, healthcare clearinghouses and their business associates to protect patient health information including payment card data. Includes Security Rule (technical safeguards), Privacy Rule (administrative and physical), and Breach Notification Rule. Specific to US healthcare organizations.
nodes.definition: Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act - US federal law protecting healthcare data privacy and security including payment card data in healthcare.
nodes.applicable_to: Healthcare providers;Health insurance companies;Healthcare clearinghouses;Business associates of healthcare organizations;Healthcare payment processors
nodes.key_features: Security Rule (technical standards); Privacy Rule (administrative/physical); Breach Notification Rule; State-specific variations; Overlaps with PCI DSS for payment card data

nodes.owner: European Union; National Cybersecurity Authorities (ENISA coordinating)
nodes.name: NIS Directive (EU) 2022/2555
nodes.description: Directive (EU) 2022/2555 governing cybersecurity for essential services including energy, transport, water, healthcare, digital infrastructure. Requires operators of essential services and certain digital service providers to maintain appropriate security measures. Enforcement by national cybersecurity authorities. Applicable to payment systems and payment infrastructure operators.
nodes.definition: EU Network and Information Systems Directive - cybersecurity requirements for critical infrastructure operators and digital service providers in the EU.
nodes.applicable_to: Critical infrastructure operators (energy, transport, water, healthcare);Payment system operators;Digital service providers with significant impact;Financial institutions providing critical services;Payment processors serving critical sectors
nodes.key_features: Risk-based security approach; Incident reporting requirements; Security baseline measures; Third-party supply chain security; Regular updates to security measures

Includes data localization requirements for payment card data. Overseen by Reserve Bank of India (RBI). Applicable to all payment processors and merchants in India.
nodes.definition: Reserve Bank of India Payment Systems Act 2007 and amendments - Indian regulation for payment system operators and processors handling card payments.
nodes.applicable_to: Payment processors in India;Payment gateways serving India;Acquiring banks in India;Indian merchants accepting cards;Card-issuing organizations in India;Third-party service providers to Indian payment systems
nodes.key_features: Data localization for Indian card transactions; Card data storage in India; RBI authorization required; Security measures standards; Customer protection requirements

nodes.owner: National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), US Department of Commerce
nodes.name: NIST Cybersecurity Framework
nodes.description: Framework developed by NIST (US Department of Commerce) providing guidelines for managing cybersecurity risk. Version 2.0 released February 2024 with updates to Core Functions: Govern (new), Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover. Widely adopted by US government and critical infrastructure. Can be used alongside PCI DSS for comprehensive security posture.
nodes.definition: National Institute of Standards and Technology Cybersecurity Framework v2.0 - US government cybersecurity guidance for managing risk and improving security practices.
nodes.applicable_to: US government contractors;Critical infrastructure;US financial institutions;Any organization seeking cybersecurity best practices;Organizations combining with PCI DSS compliance
nodes.key_features: 5 Core Functions (Govern, Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover); 23 Categories; Flexible and scalable; Not regulatory but widely adopted; Risk-based approach

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 1: Install and Maintain Network Security Controls
nodes.description: Firewalls protect the cardholder data environment from unauthorized network access. NSCs (Network Security Controls) control all inbound and outbound network traffic with a default-deny-all policy. Firewall rules must be documented and reviewed at least every six months. CDE is defined to include all components that store, process, or transmit cardholder data or sensitive authentication data. Network segmentation isolates the CDE from other networks using firewalls, routers, or other network segmentation controls.
nodes.title: Install and Maintain Network Security Controls
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Establish network security controls to protect the cardholder data environment from unauthorized network access. Implement a firewall architecture that blocks all traffic by default and allows only specifically authorized traffic based on business need. Maintain firewall rules and configurations in a documented manner reviewed regularly to ensure they continue to meet security objectives.
nodes.name: Firewall Configuration
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Firewall rules documented and approved; Default-deny-all policy implemented; Rules reviewed at least every 6 months; Network segmentation separating CDE from non-CDE; All inbound and outbound traffic subject to firewall rules; Firewall log review; Change management for firewall rules; High-availability firewall configurations; DMZ implementation if applicable; External firewall testing

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 2: Apply Secure Configurations to All System Components
nodes.description: All system components must be configured with non-default, secure configurations. Vendor-supplied default accounts must be removed or disabled. Vendor-supplied default passwords must be changed. Insecure services, protocols, and ports must be identified, classified, and disabled unless business justified. All system components must have documented and implemented configuration standards addressing known security vulnerabilities.
nodes.title: Apply Secure Configurations to All System Components
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Eliminate default security weaknesses and backdoors in all system components. Configure systems to operate securely out-of-the-box with secure defaults. Reduce the attack surface by disabling unnecessary services and using only secure communication protocols. Maintain security configuration standards to ensure consistent secure configuration across all system components.
nodes.name: Default Security Parameters
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Configuration standards documented; Default accounts removed or disabled; Vendor defaults changed for all systems; Insecure services disabled (unless documented business justification); Security patches and updates applied; Configuration baselines established; Regular configuration reviews; Hardening guidelines implemented; Secure protocols enforced (TLS 1.2+); Unnecessary ports disabled

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3: Protect Stored Cardholder Data (Requirement 3.1 - 3.7)
nodes.description: Render cardholder data unreadable at all points where it is stored through encryption, tokenization, truncation, hash-based mechanisms, or other strong cryptography. Sensitive Authentication Data (SAD) cannot be stored after transaction authorization under any circumstances, with limited exceptions for issuers. Account data storage must be kept to minimum based on business need. Formal data retention, deletion, and disposal policies must be established. PAN must be rendered unreadable in display and storage. Key management processes must be implemented with encryption key storage in HSMs/KMS.
nodes.title: Protect Stored Cardholder Data
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Protect stored cardholder data by rendering it unreadable to prevent unauthorized access. Implement strong encryption for any stored PAN. Establish clear data retention policies ensuring data is not kept longer than necessary. Never store sensitive authentication data after transaction completion. Minimize the amount of account data stored and implement secure deletion procedures.
nodes.name: Protect Stored Cardholder Data
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Data minimization policy documented; PAN rendered unreadable (encryption, tokenization, truncation, hashing); SAD never stored post-authorization; Retention policies documented and enforced; Encryption algorithm AES-256 or stronger; Key management HSM/KMS; Key rotation quarterly or semi-annually; Data deletion procedures documented and enforced; Access restrictions to stored data; Encryption key protection

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 4: Protect Cardholder Data with Strong Cryptography During Transmission
nodes.description: All cardholder data transmitted over public networks must be protected with strong cryptography (TLS 1.2 or higher). Encryption strength appropriate for the data being transmitted. Strong encryption protocols only; no fallback to insecure versions. Certificates must be valid and not expired. Point-to-Point Encryption (P2PE) may be used for payment card acceptance in physical locations. End-to-end encryption protects data from point of entry to processing system.
nodes.title: Protect Cardholder Data with Strong Cryptography During Transmission
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Protect cardholder data during transmission over public and open networks using strong cryptography. Encrypt all transmissions between systems storing/processing cardholder data. Implement TLS 1.2 minimum for all encryption. Disable support for weak cryptographic versions. Validate certificates and implement proper certificate management. Protect encryption keys appropriately.
nodes.name: Encrypt Transmission of Cardholder Data
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: TLS 1.2+ enforced; HTTPS for web applications; No fallback to SSL or weak protocols; Valid, non-expired certificates; Certificate pinning where applicable; Strong cipher suites; Key management for encryption keys; IPSec/VPN for network traffic; Encryption protocols documented; Regular testing of encryption effectiveness

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 5: Protect All Systems Against Malware
nodes.description: Anti-malware software must be deployed on all system components that can be affected by malicious software. Anti-malware tools must be actively running and kept current. Mechanisms must be capable of detecting, alerting on, and removing malware. Mechanisms must protect systems from malware and malicious activity. System logs must capture malware-related events and alerts.
nodes.title: Protect All Systems Against Malware
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Protect all system components from malicious software attacks. Deploy anti-malware tools on all systems that could be affected by malware. Maintain anti-malware definitions and tools current through automatic updates. Monitor systems for malware detection and respond to alerts. Prevent unauthorized software installation and use.
nodes.name: Malware Protection
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Anti-malware installed on all in-scope systems; Automatic updates enabled; Regular scans performed; Alerts generated for detected malware; Malware definitions current; Mechanisms actively running; Malware removed/quarantined automatically; System logs capture anti-malware alerts; Regular monitoring of anti-malware tool status

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 6: Develop and Maintain Secure Systems and Applications
nodes.description: Security patches applied timely (critical vulnerabilities within 30 days). Systems protected from known vulnerabilities. Secure development practices including design, coding, testing, and patching implemented. Security controls included in development. Source code reviewed. Vulnerabilities identified and remediated. Web applications secured against attacks. Application firewalls implemented. Secure Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC) practices enforced. Third-party libraries and components managed.
nodes.title: Develop and Maintain Secure Systems and Applications
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Develop and maintain secure systems and applications throughout their lifecycle. Implement secure coding practices and conduct regular vulnerability scanning. Apply security patches promptly, with critical patches within 30 days. Follow secure SDLC practices integrating security at every stage. Prevent vulnerabilities from being introduced via code or third-party components. Maintain secure configurations and patch management.
nodes.name: Secure Development
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Patch management process documented; Critical patches applied within 30 days; System inventory maintained; Vulnerability scanning quarterly; Penetration testing annually; Code review process; Secure coding practices; Configuration management; Source code security; Application firewall deployed; Third-party library management; Vulnerability tracking and remediation

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 7: Restrict Access to Cardholder Data by Business Need To Know
nodes.description: Access to cardholder data must be restricted based on principle of least privilege. Only personnel with documented business need should have access. Physical and logical access must be authorized and documented. Access based on business need and documented job titles/functions. Access reviewed regularly (at least annually). Access removed when no longer needed. Segregation of duties enforced. Access request and approval process documented.
nodes.title: Restrict Access to Cardholder Data by Business Need To Know
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Limit access to cardholder data strictly to those with a documented business need. Implement role-based access control (RBAC) with roles defined by job title and function. Grant access based on principle of least privilege. Review access regularly and remove unnecessary access. Maintain documentation of who has access to what data.
nodes.name: Restrict Access to Cardholder Data
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Access matrix documented; RBAC implemented; Least privilege enforced; Access based on documented business need; Job titles/functions define access; Access reviews conducted; Unnecessary access removed; Segregation of duties; Access request approval process; Termination procedures include access revocation

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 8: Identify Users and Restrict Access Through Authentication
nodes.description: User identities must be issued and managed. Unique user IDs for each person with access to systems. User authentication mechanisms must prevent unauthorized access. Strong passwords required (minimum 12 characters, complexity). Multi-factor authentication (MFA) required for all access to CDE (including administrative and remote access). Exceptions for phishing-resistant authentication factors. Password management policies enforced. Session timeouts configured. Account management documented. User access disabled after inactivity.
nodes.title: Identify Users and Restrict Access Through Authentication
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Enforce unique user identification and strong authentication to prevent unauthorized access. Implement multi-factor authentication for all CDE access. Enforce strong password policies with minimum 12 characters and complexity. Disable accounts after inactivity period (90 days recommended). Use secure authentication mechanisms preventing unauthorized access. Manage user accounts through formal processes.
nodes.name: User Identification and Authentication
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Unique user IDs assigned; MFA enabled for all CDE access; Password requirements: 12+ characters, complexity; Password history (4 previous not reused); Account lockout after failed attempts; Session timeout configured (15 min. inactive); Inactive account disablement (90 days); Account removal process; Terminal/remote access authentication; Authentication testing; MFA functioning and enforced

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 9: Restrict Physical Access to Cardholder Data
nodes.description: Physical access to facilities housing cardholder data systems must be restricted. Access controls such as badges, locks, or surveillance must be implemented. Visitor access must be logged and monitored. Physical storage of cardholder data (backup media, tapes) must be protected. Asset inventory of physical devices maintained. Media classified and securely destroyed/disposed. Off-site backups protected. Portable computing devices carrying cardholder data protected. Work in secure areas follows clear desk/clear screen policy.
nodes.title: Restrict Physical Access to Cardholder Data
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Prevent unauthorized physical access to systems and facilities housing cardholder data. Implement physical security controls restricting access to authorized personnel. Monitor and log visitor access. Protect physical storage media containing cardholder data. Ensure secure disposal of media and equipment. Maintain current inventory of equipment with cardholder data.
nodes.name: Restrict Physical Access
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Physical access controls (badges, keys, biometric); Visitor logs maintained; Video surveillance; Secure disposal procedures; Media inventory; Clear desk/screen policy; Off-site backup security; Equipment inventory tracking; Physical storage protections; Cabling security; Locked cabinets for backup media; Secure media destruction process

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 10: Log and Monitor All Access to Cardholder Data and CDE
nodes.description: All system components must log user access to cardholder data. Logs must capture user identification, date, time, resource accessed, type of access, and success/failure. Logs must be protected from tampering and deletion. Logs must be reviewed regularly (at least daily or via automated tools). Alerts configured for suspicious activity. Logs retained for minimum 12 months (3 months online). Log review process documented. Centralized log management (SIEM) recommended. User activity monitoring and anomaly detection.
nodes.title: Log and Monitor All Access to Cardholder Data and CDE
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Monitor and track all access to cardholder data and CDE to detect unauthorized access. Maintain audit logs recording who accessed what, when, and whether successful. Protect logs from modification or deletion. Review logs regularly to identify suspicious activity and anomalies. Respond to identified security events.
nodes.name: Track and Monitor Network Access
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Logging enabled on all systems; Logs capture: timestamp, user ID, resource, action type, success/failure; Log protection (tamper-proof); Daily/automated log review; Alerts for suspicious activity; 12-month minimum retention; 3 months online; User activity monitoring; Real-time alerting for critical events; Log aggregation (SIEM); Anomaly detection; Forensic log preservation

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 11: Test Security of Systems and Processes Regularly
nodes.description: Quarterly external network vulnerability scans by Approved Scanning Vendor (ASV). Scans include all known vulnerabilities and systems exposed to internet. Annual penetration testing of all systems and networks. Internal vulnerability scans at least quarterly. Identified vulnerabilities remediated and re-scanned. Network segmentation validation to ensure CDE isolation. Wireless access point detection quarterly. Intrusion detection and prevention systems implemented and tested. Change-detection mechanisms in place. Security testing documented and tracked.
nodes.title: Test Security of Systems and Processes Regularly
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Regularly test and validate that security systems and controls are functioning effectively. Conduct vulnerability assessments to identify weaknesses before attackers. Perform penetration testing to validate security controls. Validate network segmentation. Test intrusion detection systems. Conduct regular configuration reviews.
nodes.name: Regular Security Testing
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: ASV quarterly scans; Scans include all known vulnerabilities; Remediation of vulnerabilities; Penetration testing annually; Internal vulnerability scans quarterly; Network segmentation validation; Wireless AP detection quarterly; IDS/IPS testing; Change detection mechanisms; Configuration reviews; Segmentation validation; Scan reports documented

nodes.criticality: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 12: Maintain Security Policies and Programs
nodes.description: Security policy documented, kept current, and communicated to all affected parties. Annual information security awareness training provided to all employees. Breach notification procedures established and documented. Incident response procedures documented and tested. Third-party service provider compliance verified annually. Roles and responsibilities assigned and documented. Risk assessment processes established and regular. Enforcement of security policies demonstrated. Contracts with service providers include security requirements. Management acknowledgment of responsibility for compliance. Board or executive-level responsibility for security.
nodes.title: Maintain Security Policies and Programs
nodes.purpose_and_intent: Establish and maintain comprehensive security policies addressing all 12 PCI DSS requirements and organizational security practices. Communicate policies to all affected personnel through training and awareness programs. Enforce policies consistently. Maintain governance and oversight ensuring continued compliance. Manage third-party relationships and their compliance obligations.
nodes.name: Information Security Policy
nodes.key_implementation_requirements: Security policy documented and approved; Annual review and updates; Distribution to all personnel; Annual awareness training; Role-based training; Breach notification procedures; Incident response plan; Third-party management program; Annual service provider verification; Risk assessment process; Incident testing/drills; Management accountability; Board oversight; Contract compliance clauses

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Any merchant that has suffered a data breach or an attacker has compromised their account data, or any merchant processing over 6 million Visa transactions annually (across all channels) or over 2.5 million Mastercard transactions annually. Includes brick-and-mortar, e-commerce, mail/telephone order merchants.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA; Report on Compliance (RoC); Attestation of Compliance (AOC); Quarterly network scans by ASV
nodes.transaction_threshold: Greater than 6 million Visa transactions/year OR Greater than 2.5 million Mastercard transactions/year
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory; Annual QSA audit required; Quarterly external vulnerability scans by Approved Scanning Vendor (ASV); Annual penetration testing; Quarterly internal vulnerability scans; Network segmentation documentation; Incident response plan; Security awareness training program; Asset inventory; Firewall review
nodes.name: Merchant Level 1
nodes.definition: Largest merchants by annual card transaction volume. Organizations processing over 6 million Visa transactions per year or over 2.5 million Mastercard transactions per year. Typically large retailers, e-commerce platforms, multinational corporations, airlines, hospitality chains, and major service providers with extensive payment card operations.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1; ISO 27001 (recommended); SOC 2 Type II (recommended); GDPR (if EU operations); CCPA (if California operations); Payment Brand specific requirements (Visa, Mastercard, Amex, Discover, JCB)

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Any merchant processing 1 million to 6 million Visa transactions annually or 150,000 to 2.5 million Mastercard transactions annually across all channels. Subject to mandatory annual assessments and reporting requirements similar to Level 1 merchants.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA; Report on Compliance (RoC); Attestation of Compliance (AOC); Quarterly network scans by ASV
nodes.transaction_threshold: 1.5 million to 6 million Visa transactions/year OR 150,000 to 2.5 million Mastercard transactions/year
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory; Annual QSA audit required; Quarterly external vulnerability scans by Approved Scanning Vendor (ASV); Annual penetration testing; Quarterly internal vulnerability scans; Network segmentation recommended; Incident response plan; Security awareness training; Vendor management program; Change control procedures
nodes.name: Merchant Level 2
nodes.definition: Mid-to-large size merchants processing between 1.5 million and 6 million Visa transactions annually or between 150,000 and 2.5 million Mastercard transactions annually. Includes regional retailers, medium e-commerce businesses, restaurant chains, healthcare providers, educational institutions, and growing enterprises.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1; ISO 27001 (recommended); SOC 2 (recommended); GDPR (if EU operations); CCPA (if California operations); Industry-specific regulations

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Any merchant processing 20,000 to 1 million Visa e-commerce transactions annually or 20,000 to 150,000 Mastercard e-commerce transactions annually. Self-assessment permitted with appropriate attestation and quarterly scanning requirements.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ); Attestation of Compliance (AOC); Quarterly network scans by ASV
nodes.transaction_threshold: 20,000 to 1.5 million Visa e-commerce transactions/year OR 20,000 to 150,000 Mastercard e-commerce transactions/year
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory; Annual Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ A, A-EP, B, C, or D based on processing method); Attestation of Compliance signed by officer; Quarterly external vulnerability scans by ASV; Annual internal vulnerability scans; Security policies documented; Incident response procedures; Vendor security management; Training records maintained
nodes.name: Merchant Level 3
nodes.definition: Small-to-medium size merchants processing between 20,000 and 1.5 million Visa e-commerce transactions annually or between 20,000 and 150,000 Mastercard e-commerce transactions annually. Includes small retailers, online businesses, professional services, non-profits, and emerging technology companies.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1; GDPR (if EU operations); CCPA (if California operations); Payment Brand requirements; Industry-specific standards as applicable

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Any merchant processing fewer than 20,000 Visa e-commerce transactions annually and all other merchants processing up to 1 million Visa transactions annually or up to 150,000 Mastercard transactions annually. May complete Self-Assessment Questionnaire with reduced validation requirements.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ); Compliance Validation may be required by Acquirer; Quarterly network scans by ASV (if applicable)
nodes.transaction_threshold: Fewer than 20,000 Visa e-commerce transactions/year AND up to 1.5 million Visa transactions/year (all channels) OR up to 150,000 Mastercard transactions/year
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements apply (validation methods vary); Annual Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ A, A-EP, B, C, or D); Compliance validation as required by acquiring bank; Quarterly scans for e-commerce merchants; Security policies appropriate to size; Basic security controls implemented; Payment application security; Third-party provider management
nodes.name: Merchant Level 4
nodes.definition: Smallest merchants by transaction volume processing fewer than 20,000 Visa e-commerce transactions annually and all other merchants (regardless of acceptance channel) processing up to 1.5 million Visa transactions annually or up to 150,000 Mastercard transactions annually. Includes small businesses, sole proprietors, local shops, service providers, and micro-merchants.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1; GDPR (if applicable); Regional data protection laws; Payment Brand requirements; Acquirer-specific requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Any third-party entity that is not a payment brand and is directly involved in the processing, storage, or transmission of cardholder data. Level 1 Service Providers process, store, or transmit over 300,000 Visa transactions annually OR have suffered a breach OR are deemed critical by payment brands. Must register with payment brands.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA; Report on Compliance (RoC); Attestation of Compliance (AOC) submitted to payment brands; Quarterly network scans by ASV
nodes.transaction_threshold: Greater than 300,000 Visa transactions/year OR deemed critical by payment brands
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory; Annual QSA audit required; Report on Compliance submitted to all applicable payment brands; Attestation of Compliance; Quarterly external vulnerability scans by ASV; Annual penetration testing; Quarterly internal vulnerability scans; Comprehensive security program; Incident response and breach notification; Service provider registration with Visa/Mastercard; Vendor risk management; Multi-tenant security controls
nodes.name: Service Provider Level 1
nodes.definition: Largest third-party service providers by transaction volume or criticality. Any service provider processing, storing, or transmitting over 300,000 Visa transactions annually or designated by payment brands as Level 1 due to criticality. Includes major payment processors, payment gateways, hosting providers, cloud service providers, managed security providers, and technology vendors serving merchants.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS/PTS (if applicable); ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II; GDPR (if EU operations); CCPA (if California); Cloud Security Alliance (CSA); Industry-specific compliance (HIPAA for healthcare, etc.)

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Any service provider processing, storing, or transmitting fewer than 300,000 Visa transactions annually. May complete Self-Assessment Questionnaire instead of QSA audit subject to payment brand and acquirer requirements. Must maintain compliance program and documentation.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ D for Service Providers); Attestation of Compliance (AOC); Quarterly network scans by ASV; Additional validation may be required by clients or payment brands
nodes.transaction_threshold: Fewer than 300,000 Visa transactions/year
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory; Annual Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ D-Service Provider); Attestation of Compliance; Quarterly external vulnerability scans by ASV; Annual penetration testing; Quarterly internal vulnerability scans; Security policies and procedures; Third-party vendor assessment; Client security responsibility matrix; Service provider agreement templates; Annual review and update
nodes.name: Service Provider Level 2
nodes.definition: Mid-size third-party service providers processing or handling fewer than 300,000 Visa transactions annually. Includes regional payment processors, smaller payment gateways, IT service providers, software vendors, SaaS platforms, telecommunications providers, and consultancies supporting payment environments.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); ISO 27001 (recommended); SOC 2 Type II (recommended); GDPR (if applicable); CCPA (if applicable); Cloud security standards; Industry-specific regulations

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Member or organization that processes payment card transactions on behalf of merchants and connects to payment networks for authorization and settlement. Processors handle large volumes of sensitive authentication data and cardholder data. Subject to stringent security requirements and oversight by payment brands and card networks.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA; Report on Compliance (RoC); Attestation of Compliance (AOC); Quarterly network scans; Continuous monitoring; Payment brand audits
nodes.transaction_threshold: Processes millions to billions of transactions annually for multiple merchants
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory; Annual QSA comprehensive audit; Payment brand security assessments; Network security controls; HSM (Hardware Security Module) management; Encryption key management; Multi-factor authentication; Segregation of duties; 24/7 security operations center; Real-time fraud monitoring; Incident response; Business continuity; Disaster recovery; Vendor management; Compliance reporting to payment brands; Annual penetration testing; Quarterly vulnerability scans (internal and external)
nodes.name: Payment Processor
nodes.definition: Organizations that facilitate payment transactions between merchants and payment networks. Responsibilities include transaction authorization, clearing, settlement, encryption/decryption of payment data, fraud detection, and compliance monitoring. Includes front-end processors, back-end processors, and integrated payment service providers.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS/PTS (Payment Application security); PCI PIN (for PIN processing); ISO 27001; SOC 1 Type II; SOC 2 Type II; GDPR (global operations); Regional data protection laws; Banking regulations; Payment network operating rules (Visa, Mastercard, etc.); FFIEC guidance (US)

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Member financial institution or bank that processes payment card transactions for merchants and maintains merchant relationships. Acquirers are responsible for ensuring merchant compliance with PCI DSS, enforcing security requirements, validating merchant compliance levels, and reporting to payment brands. Subject to payment brand audits and regulatory oversight.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA; Report on Compliance (RoC); Attestation of Compliance; Payment brand compliance validation; Regulatory examinations; Quarterly scans
nodes.transaction_threshold: Manages thousands to millions of merchant accounts processing billions in transaction volume
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory for acquirer infrastructure; Annual QSA audit; Payment brand security programs; Merchant compliance monitoring program; Merchant onboarding security validation; Risk-based merchant compliance level assignment; Quarterly merchant scan validation; Compromise investigation procedures; Regulatory compliance (banking regulations); Anti-money laundering (AML) programs; Know Your Customer (KYC); Fraud monitoring; Merchant agreement security clauses; Penalty enforcement; Incident response; Business continuity
nodes.name: Acquiring Bank (Acquirer)
nodes.definition: Financial institutions that establish and maintain relationships with merchants to enable them to accept payment cards. Responsibilities include merchant underwriting, PCI DSS compliance enforcement, transaction processing contracts, dispute resolution, and regulatory compliance. Subject to payment brand requirements and banking regulations.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); ISO 27001; SOC 1 Type II; SOC 2 Type II; GDPR (if applicable); Banking regulations (Basel III, Dodd-Frank, etc.); Anti-Money Laundering (AML); Know Your Customer (KYC); OFAC compliance; Payment brand operating rules; Regional banking regulations; Financial services sector-specific standards

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Member financial institution or bank that issues payment cards to cardholders. Issuers are responsible for cardholder authentication, authorization of transactions, account management, and protection of cardholder data including Sensitive Authentication Data (SAD). Must comply with PCI DSS for systems storing, processing, or transmitting cardholder data. Subject to payment brand oversight.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA; Report on Compliance (RoC); Attestation of Compliance; Payment brand audits; Regulatory examinations; Continuous monitoring
nodes.transaction_threshold: Issues millions of payment cards; processes billions in authorization requests
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory; Annual QSA audit for issuer processing systems; Payment brand security requirements; Cardholder authentication systems (EMV, 3D Secure); Fraud detection and prevention; Account management security; Sensitive Authentication Data (SAD) handling (must NOT store post-authorization); Cryptographic key management; HSM deployment; Multi-factor authentication; Mobile banking security; Online banking security; Call center security; Card production security; PIN management; Regulatory compliance; Incident response; Breach notification; Business continuity
nodes.name: Issuing Bank (Issuer)
nodes.definition: Financial institutions that issue payment cards to cardholders and maintain cardholder accounts. Responsibilities include card issuance, cardholder authentication, transaction authorization decisions, fraud management, account management, and cardholder data protection. Subject to payment brand and banking regulations.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PCI PIN (for PIN-based cards); EMV specifications; 3-D Secure; ISO 27001; SOC 1 Type II; SOC 2 Type II; GDPR; Banking regulations; Consumer protection laws; Anti-Money Laundering (AML); Know Your Customer (KYC); Regional financial services regulations; Payment brand operating rules (Visa Core Rules, Mastercard Standards)

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Service provider that provides payment gateway services connecting merchant websites/applications to payment processors. Gateways transmit and may temporarily store cardholder data. Critical service provider requiring comprehensive security controls including network security, encryption, tokenization, fraud detection, and secure APIs.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA (Level 1) or SAQ D-Service Provider (Level 2); Attestation of Compliance; Quarterly ASV scans
nodes.transaction_threshold: Varies by transaction volume processed; typically Level 1 if processing over 300,000 transactions/year
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements; Network segmentation; TLS 1.2+ encryption; Tokenization services; Hosted payment page security; API security; PCI DSS scoping; Multi-tenant environment security; Fraud detection; Transaction monitoring; Developer security training; Secure coding practices; Penetration testing; Vulnerability management; Incident response; 24/7 monitoring; Uptime/availability SLAs; Data breach insurance; Quarterly scans; Annual penetration testing
nodes.name: Payment Gateway Provider
nodes.definition: Technology service providers that facilitate online payment processing by securely transmitting transaction data between merchants (e-commerce sites) and payment processors or acquiring banks. Includes hosted payment pages, API-based gateways, and integrated payment solutions for web and mobile applications.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS (if applicable); ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II; GDPR; CCPA; Cloud security standards; API security standards (OAuth, OpenID); Web application security (OWASP); Payment brand requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Service provider offering cloud computing services (IaaS, PaaS, SaaS) that stores, processes, or transmits cardholder data or provides infrastructure for cardholder data environments. Responsible for infrastructure security, network segmentation, encryption, access controls, and shared responsibility model documentation. Must maintain PCI DSS compliance for services in scope.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual QSA Assessment (Level 1) or SAQ D-Service Provider (Level 2); Attestation of Compliance; Quarterly scans; Third-party audit reports (SOC 2)
nodes.transaction_threshold: Varies by volume; Level 1 if critical or high transaction volume
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements for in-scope systems; Shared responsibility matrix clearly defined; Infrastructure security controls; Network virtualization security; Multi-tenancy controls; Container security; Encryption at rest and in transit; Key management; Access control and identity management; Logging and monitoring; Backup and recovery; Physical data center security; Compliance inheritance documentation; Customer responsibility documentation; Security configuration baselines; Vulnerability scanning; Penetration testing; Incident response; Breach notification; Service provider registration
nodes.name: Cloud Service Provider (Hosting CHD)
nodes.definition: Cloud infrastructure, platform, or software service providers that host, store, or process cardholder data on behalf of merchants or service providers. Includes Infrastructure-as-a-Service (IaaS), Platform-as-a-Service (PaaS), and Software-as-a-Service (SaaS) providers supporting payment applications or cardholder data environments.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II; CSA STAR Certification; GDPR; HIPAA (if applicable); FedRAMP (for government clients); Regional data sovereignty laws; Cloud security frameworks; Payment brand requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Service provider offering managed security services that monitor, manage, or have access to cardholder data environments or security controls protecting cardholder data. MSSPs must maintain PCI DSS compliance for their infrastructure and demonstrate secure practices for accessing client environments. Responsible for security control effectiveness and monitoring.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual QSA Assessment or SAQ D-Service Provider; Attestation of Compliance; Quarterly ASV scans; Client audit rights
nodes.transaction_threshold: Varies; typically Level 1 if managing critical infrastructure for Level 1 entities
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements for MSSP infrastructure; Secure remote access (MFA required); Network segmentation between clients; Least privilege access; Monitoring and logging of administrative access; Incident response procedures; Security operations center (SOC) security; SIEM platform security; Vulnerability management; Threat intelligence; Client data segregation; Secure communication channels; Personnel background checks; Security awareness training; Non-disclosure agreements; Service level agreements; Right-to-audit clauses; Third-party risk management; Annual security assessments
nodes.name: Managed Security Service Provider (MSSP)
nodes.definition: Organizations providing managed security services for entities handling cardholder data. Services include managed firewall, intrusion detection/prevention, SIEM monitoring, vulnerability scanning, log management, incident response, and security operations center (SOC) services for payment environments.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II; ISO 27017 (cloud security); ISO 27018 (cloud privacy); GDPR; Regional data protection laws; NIST Cybersecurity Framework; Industry-specific standards

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Merchant that accepts payment cards through e-commerce channels (websites, mobile apps, APIs) where the cardholder and payment card are not physically present at the point of sale. Subject to all PCI DSS requirements with specific focus on web application security, transmission security, tokenization, fraud prevention, and secure payment pages. Compliance level varies by transaction volume.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); Typically SAQ A or A-EP for hosted payment pages, SAQ D for direct processing
nodes.transaction_threshold: Compliance level determined by annual e-commerce transaction volume (see Level 1-4 thresholds)
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements; Web application firewall (WAF); Secure coding practices; Input validation; Output encoding; SQL injection prevention; Cross-site scripting (XSS) prevention; Authentication and session management; TLS 1.2+ for all transmission; Tokenization (recommended); Hosted payment page (recommended); PCI DSS SAQ A or A-EP scoping; fraud detection; 3D Secure authentication; Address Verification Service (AVS); Card Verification Value (CVV) validation; Velocity checks; IP geolocation; Device fingerprinting; Security awareness training; Quarterly ASV scans; Annual penetration testing
nodes.name: E-commerce Merchant (Card Not Present)
nodes.definition: Merchants conducting business primarily or exclusively through online channels where payment cards are not physically present. Includes online retailers, subscription services, digital goods providers, software-as-a-service (SaaS) vendors, and marketplace platforms. Higher fraud risk due to card-not-present transactions.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS (for payment applications); OWASP Top 10; Web application security standards; GDPR (if EU customers); CCPA (if California customers); Consumer protection laws; E-commerce platform security; Payment gateway security; Regional data protection laws

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Merchant accepting payment cards through face-to-face channels where the cardholder presents the physical card at point-of-sale. Includes magnetic stripe swipe, EMV chip card insertion, and contactless/NFC payments. Subject to all PCI DSS requirements with focus on physical security, POS security, and card reader protection. Compliance level varies by transaction volume.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); Typically SAQ B or C for EMV terminals, SAQ D for integrated systems
nodes.transaction_threshold: Compliance level determined by annual transaction volume across all channels (see Level 1-4 thresholds)
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements; Secure POS terminals; EMV chip card acceptance; P2PE (Point-to-Point Encryption) recommended; Physical security of POS devices; Tamper-evident seals; POS terminal inspection procedures; Network segmentation (isolate payment network); Secure remote access to POS; POS software security patches; Anti-malware on POS systems; Contactless payment security; Mobile POS security; Card reader security; Receipt security (mask PAN); Employee training on card handling; Physical access controls to back-office; Video surveillance; SAQ validation; Quarterly scans; Penetration testing (Level 1-2)
nodes.name: Retail Merchant (Card Present)
nodes.definition: Merchants conducting business in physical locations where payment cards are physically presented for transactions. Includes brick-and-mortar stores, restaurants, gas stations, hotels, and face-to-face service providers. Uses point-of-sale (POS) terminals, card readers, and EMV chip card technology.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS/PTS for POS applications; P2PE standards (if applicable); EMV specifications; ISO 27001 (optional); Regional retail security standards; Consumer protection laws; Labor regulations; Payment brand requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Merchant processing payment card transactions through multiple acceptance channels (in-store, online, mobile, phone, etc.) requiring comprehensive security controls across all environments. Must scope all channels, implement consistent security controls, and coordinate compliance across different processing methods. Compliance level typically Level 1 or 2 due to volume and complexity.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual QSA Assessment (typically required due to complexity); Report on Compliance covering all channels; Quarterly ASV scans; Annual penetration testing; SAQ may be possible for smaller omnichannel merchants
nodes.transaction_threshold: Varies; typically high volume due to multiple channels; Often exceeds 6 million transactions/year
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements across all channels; Network segmentation per channel; E-commerce security (TLS, WAF, secure coding); POS security (EMV, P2PE); Call center security (prohibit recording CVV, secure IVR); Mobile app security; API security; Tokenization across channels; Centralized logging and monitoring; Unified incident response; Cross-channel fraud detection; Consistent access controls; Employee training for all channels; Third-party vendor management; Compliance program management; Comprehensive security policies; Quarterly scans for all external IPs; Annual penetration testing (all channels); Network diagrams documenting all environments; Data flow diagrams; Cardholder data inventory
nodes.name: Omnichannel Merchant
nodes.definition: Merchants accepting payment cards through multiple channels including physical stores, e-commerce websites, mobile applications, call centers (mail order/telephone order), and social commerce. Complex compliance requirements due to multiple payment acceptance methods and integrated customer data across channels.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS/PTS; P2PE; ISO 27001 (recommended); SOC 2 (if SaaS components); GDPR; CCPA; Consumer protection laws; Channel-specific regulations; E-commerce platform security; POS security; Payment brand requirements; Industry-specific standards

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Service provider that facilitates payment card acceptance for multiple sub-merchants under a master merchant account. PayFacs are responsible for sub-merchant compliance with PCI DSS, must maintain their own compliance, validate sub-merchant security, and report to payment brands. Subject to enhanced oversight due to sub-merchant liability.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA; Report on Compliance (RoC); Attestation of Compliance (AOC); Quarterly ASV scans; Payment brand registration and ongoing reporting
nodes.transaction_threshold: Aggregates transactions for potentially thousands of sub-merchants; typically processes over 300,000 transactions annually
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements for PayFac infrastructure; Sub-merchant onboarding security validation; Risk-based sub-merchant compliance monitoring; Sub-merchant compliance level assignment; Attestation of sub-merchant compliance; Sub-merchant SAQ validation; Quarterly scan coordination for sub-merchants; Incident response for sub-merchant breaches; Sub-merchant agreement security clauses; Fraud monitoring across sub-merchant portfolio; Know Your Customer (KYC) for sub-merchants; Reserve account management; Chargeback management; Regulatory compliance (money transmitter licenses); Payment brand registration; Payment brand reporting; Penalty management for sub-merchant non-compliance
nodes.name: Payment Facilitator (PayFac)
nodes.definition: Third-party service providers that enable sub-merchants (often small businesses) to accept payment cards without establishing their own direct merchant accounts. PayFacs assume liability and compliance responsibility for sub-merchants, performing underwriting, onboarding, and compliance monitoring. Also called aggregators or master merchants.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II; Payment brand operating rules; Money transmitter regulations; Anti-Money Laundering (AML); Know Your Customer (KYC); GDPR; CCPA; Regional payment facilitator regulations; Payment gateway security standards

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Third-party software vendor developing payment applications used by merchants or service providers to process, store, or transmit cardholder data. ISVs are responsible for secure software development lifecycle, security testing, vulnerability remediation, and ongoing security support. Applications may require PA-DSS validation or adherence to PCI Secure Software Standard.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual QSA Assessment or SAQ D-Service Provider; PA-DSS validation (if applicable); Attestation of Compliance; Security testing results
nodes.transaction_threshold: Varies by deployment scale; Level 1 if software widely deployed or processing for Level 1 merchants
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements for development environment and infrastructure; Secure Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC); Threat modeling; Secure coding standards (OWASP); Code review (manual and automated); Static Application Security Testing (SAST); Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST); Penetration testing; Vulnerability remediation; PA-DSS validation (if storing, processing, or transmitting CHD); PCI Secure Software Standard compliance; Software composition analysis (third-party libraries); Security patch management; Customer security guidance; Application hardening documentation; Secure default configurations; Customer implementation validation; Developer security training
nodes.name: Independent Software Vendor (ISV)
nodes.definition: Software developers and vendors that create payment applications, point-of-sale software, shopping carts, payment modules, mobile payment apps, or other software that processes, stores, or transmits cardholder data. ISVs must ensure applications are developed securely and validated against PA-DSS or PCI SSC standards.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS/PCI Secure Software Standard; ISO 27001; OWASP; Secure coding standards; GDPR; CCPA; Software supply chain security; DevSecOps frameworks; Application security standards; Payment brand requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Service provider that has access to, or could impact the security of, cardholder data or the cardholder data environment but does not store, process, or transmit cardholder data as part of service delivery. TPSPs must maintain security controls appropriate to their access level and scope of services. Subject to PCI DSS requirements for systems they manage or access.
nodes.assessment_type: SAQ D-Service Provider; Attestation of Compliance; May require QSA audit based on client requirements or scope
nodes.transaction_threshold: Not determined by transaction volume; based on scope of access and criticality
nodes.compliance_requirements: PCI DSS requirements based on scope of services provided; Secure remote access (VPN with MFA); Least privilege access; Access control management; Authentication requirements; Activity logging and monitoring; Background checks for personnel; Non-disclosure agreements; Security awareness training; Incident response coordination; Vulnerability management for systems accessed; Secure disposal of client data; Service level agreements with security clauses; Right-to-audit provisions; Third-party risk assessments; Insurance (E&O, cyber liability); Compliance monitoring and reporting; Quarterly reviews of access; Annual compliance validation
nodes.name: Third-Party Service Organization (TPSP)
nodes.definition: Any external organization providing services that impact the security of cardholder data environments but may not directly process cardholder data. Includes IT consulting firms, system integrators, network engineers, database administrators, auditors, and support providers with access to systems or networks containing cardholder data.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory for scope); ISO 27001 (recommended); SOC 2 Type II (recommended); GDPR (if applicable); Industry-specific regulations; Professional standards (consulting); Regional data protection laws; Payment brand requirements; Client-specific security requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Service provider offering payment acceptance through mobile devices (smartphones, tablets) or mobile applications. Includes mobile wallet providers, mPOS vendors, and in-app payment processors. Responsible for mobile application security, device security, secure data storage on mobile devices, and protection of cardholder data in mobile environments. Subject to PCI Mobile Payment Acceptance Security Guidelines.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual QSA Assessment (Level 1) or SAQ D-Service Provider (Level 2); Attestation of Compliance; Quarterly ASV scans; Mobile application security testing
nodes.transaction_threshold: Varies by transaction volume and deployment scale; Level 1 if exceeding 300,000 transactions/year
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements; PCI Mobile Payment Guidelines compliance; Mobile application security testing; Secure coding for mobile apps; Encryption of data at rest on mobile devices; Secure data transmission (TLS 1.2+); Mobile device security (jailbreak/root detection); Biometric authentication support; Tokenization (recommended); EMV/NFC security (contactless payments); Bluetooth security (card readers); Mobile SDK security; API security; Multi-factor authentication; Device attestation; Remote wipe capabilities; Secure key storage (Keychain/Keystore); Certificate pinning; Obfuscation; App store security review; Penetration testing; Quarterly vulnerability scanning; Incident response
nodes.name: Mobile Payment Provider
nodes.definition: Service providers offering mobile payment solutions including mobile wallets, person-to-person (P2P) payment apps, in-app payment processing, mobile point-of-sale (mPOS) solutions, contactless payment services (NFC), and QR code payment systems. Handles payment data on mobile devices.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PCI Mobile Payment Acceptance Guidelines; PA-DSS (if applicable); EMV specifications; ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II; GDPR; CCPA; Mobile platform security guidelines (Apple, Google); OWASP Mobile Top 10; Payment brand requirements; Regional mobile payment regulations

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Service provider offering telecommunications or network services used to transmit cardholder data between merchants, processors, and payment networks. Responsible for network security, transmission encryption, access controls, and protection of cardholder data in transit. Scope limited to network segments handling payment data.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual QSA Assessment or SAQ D-Service Provider based on volume and criticality; Attestation of Compliance; Quarterly ASV scans
nodes.transaction_threshold: Varies by scope; Level 1 if providing critical network infrastructure for payment processing
nodes.compliance_requirements: PCI DSS requirements applicable to network infrastructure in scope; Network segmentation; Encryption of cardholder data in transit (TLS 1.2+); Network access controls; Firewall configurations; Intrusion detection/prevention systems; Network monitoring and logging; Physical security of network infrastructure; Secure remote access (MFA); Change control for network configurations; Vendor management (hardware, software); Vulnerability management; Penetration testing of network infrastructure; Incident response; Business continuity; Disaster recovery; DDoS protection; Network availability SLAs; Documentation of network architecture
nodes.name: Telecommunications Provider
nodes.definition: Telecommunications companies providing network connectivity, voice services, or infrastructure supporting payment card transactions. Includes internet service providers (ISPs), telecom carriers, network service providers, and companies offering point-of-sale dial-up or broadband connectivity for payment processing.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (scope-dependent); ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II; Telecommunications regulations (FCC, regional telecom authorities); Network security standards; GDPR; Regional data protection laws; Payment brand requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: SaaS provider offering cloud-based applications that handle cardholder data on behalf of customers. Responsible for application security, infrastructure security, multi-tenant security, data isolation, secure APIs, and shared responsibility model. Customers and SaaS provider share PCI DSS compliance responsibilities based on service delivery model.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual QSA Assessment (Level 1) or SAQ D-Service Provider (Level 2); Attestation of Compliance; Quarterly ASV scans; SOC 2 Type II audit recommended
nodes.transaction_threshold: Varies by transaction volume and customer base; Level 1 if exceeding 300,000 transactions/year or serving Level 1 merchants

nodes.name: Software-as-a-Service (SaaS) Provider
nodes.definition: Cloud-based software providers offering applications that process, store, or transmit cardholder data. Includes subscription management platforms, billing systems, customer relationship management (CRM) systems with payment processing, accounting software with payment features, and vertical-specific SaaS platforms (e.g., restaurant, retail, healthcare).
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS/PCI Secure Software Standard (if applicable); ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II (highly recommended); CSA STAR; GDPR; CCPA; HIPAA (if healthcare); Industry-specific regulations; Cloud security frameworks; OWASP; Secure coding standards; Payment brand requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Processor providing transaction processing services connecting acquiring banks to payment card networks (Visa, Mastercard, etc.). Handles transaction authorization requests, clearing files, settlement processing, and reporting. Processes large volumes of sensitive payment data requiring comprehensive security controls, network security, encryption, access controls, and operational resilience.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA; Report on Compliance (RoC); Attestation of Compliance (AOC); Payment brand security assessments; Quarterly ASV scans; Continuous monitoring
nodes.transaction_threshold: Processes millions to billions of transactions annually for multiple acquiring banks and thousands of merchants
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements mandatory; Annual QSA comprehensive audit; Payment network security requirements; Hardware Security Module (HSM) management; Cryptographic key management; Network security controls (firewalls, IDS/IPS); Secure authorization routing; Clearing and settlement security; Multi-factor authentication; Privileged access management; Segregation of duties; 24/7 security operations center (SOC); Real-time transaction monitoring; Fraud detection systems; Incident response; Business continuity; Disaster recovery; Redundancy and failover; Compliance reporting to payment brands; Quarterly vulnerability scans; Annual penetration testing; Third-party vendor management
nodes.name: Merchant Acquirer Processor
nodes.definition: Organizations that provide back-end processing services for acquiring banks, handling transaction authorization routing, clearing, settlement, and reporting. Connects acquiring banks to payment networks and card issuers. Critical infrastructure requiring highest security controls and 24/7 operations.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PCI PIN (if PIN processing); ISO 27001; SOC 1 Type II; SOC 2 Type II; Payment network operating rules (VisaNet, Mastercard Banknet); Regional financial regulations; Banking regulations; GDPR; Regional data protection laws; FFIEC guidance (US)

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Merchant accepting payment cards via mail or telephone where the cardholder provides card information remotely without physical card presentation. Subject to all PCI DSS requirements with specific focus on call center security, secure handling of written orders, prohibition on recording full PAN or CVV, Interactive Voice Response (IVR) security, and employee training on secure card data handling.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); Typically SAQ C-VT for phone/mail order processing
nodes.transaction_threshold: Compliance level determined by annual transaction volume across all channels (see Level 1-4 thresholds)
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements; Call center security controls; Prohibition on recording cardholder data (audio recordings must not capture PAN or CVV); Dual-Tone Multi-Frequency (DTMF) masking; Interactive Voice Response (IVR) security; Secure storage of written orders; PAN masking on paper forms; Physical security for mail order forms; Shredding/secure disposal of documents containing CHD; Employee training on PCI DSS; Access controls to cardholder data; Screen masking during data entry; Secure transmission to payment processor (TLS 1.2+); Fraud prevention (AVS, CVV validation); Monitoring and logging of access; Security awareness for call center staff; Quarterly ASV scans; Penetration testing (Level 1-2)
nodes.name: Card-Not-Present Merchant (Mail Order / Telephone Order)
nodes.definition: Merchants accepting payment card transactions where the card is not physically presented, specifically through mail order or telephone (phone) order channels. Includes catalog retailers, call centers, telemarketing, subscription services, and businesses processing orders via written forms or phone. Higher fraud risk compared to card-present transactions.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS (for payment applications); Telemarketing regulations; Consumer protection laws; Do Not Call regulations; GDPR (if EU customers); CCPA (if California customers); Telephone Consumer Protection Act (US); Call center security standards; Payment brand requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Merchant storing cardholder data (Primary Account Number) for future recurring transactions. Higher PCI DSS requirements due to data storage. Must encrypt stored PAN, implement strict access controls, and maintain comprehensive security program. Subject to enhanced scrutiny and higher compliance requirements compared to merchants not storing cardholder data.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); Typically SAQ D due to cardholder data storage
nodes.transaction_threshold: Compliance level determined by annual transaction volume (see Level 1-4 thresholds); Often Level 2-3 due to business model

nodes.name: Subscription / Recurring Billing Merchant
nodes.definition: Merchants that store cardholder data for recurring billing purposes. Includes subscription services (streaming, software-as-a-service, membership organizations), utilities, insurance companies, recurring donation platforms, and any business model charging customers on a recurring schedule (monthly, annually, etc.).
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS (for billing applications); ISO 27001 (recommended); GDPR (right to deletion, data minimization); CCPA; Consumer protection laws; Subscription billing regulations; Auto-renewal disclosure laws; Regional data protection laws; Payment brand requirements

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Hospitality merchant accepting payment cards for lodging, food service, or entertainment. Subject to all PCI DSS requirements with specific considerations for property management systems, restaurant POS systems, reservations systems, gift card programs, and integration challenges between multiple systems. Compliance level based on annual transaction volume.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); Often SAQ D due to complex integrated systems
nodes.compliance_level: Varies (Level 1-4 based on transaction volume); Large chains typically Level 1-2
nodes.transaction_threshold: Compliance level determined by annual transaction volume across all properties and channels

nodes.name: Hospitality Merchant (Hotels / Restaurants)
nodes.definition: Merchants in hospitality industry including hotels, resorts, restaurants, bars, catering services, food delivery platforms, and entertainment venues. Often process high volumes of card-present and card-not-present transactions with unique PCI DSS challenges including property management systems (PMS), point-of-sale systems, advance reservations, and authorization holds.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); PA-DSS/PTS (POS/PMS applications); P2PE (recommended); GDPR (if EU guests); CCPA (if California); Hospitality industry standards; Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) compliance; Health department regulations (restaurants); Payment brand requirements; State/local hospitality regulations

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Healthcare entity accepting payment cards for medical services or products. Must comply with PCI DSS for payment card data protection AND HIPAA for protected health information (PHI). Requires careful segregation of cardholder data and health information, separate security controls, and coordination between PCI DSS and HIPAA compliance programs. Compliance level based on transaction volume.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); SAQ type depends on payment processing method
nodes.compliance_level: Varies (Level 1-4 based on transaction volume); Most healthcare providers Level 3-4
nodes.transaction_threshold: Compliance level determined by annual card transaction volume (see Level 1-4 thresholds)
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements; Clear segregation of PCI and HIPAA data; Separate security controls for CHD vs PHI; Point-of-sale security (reception desks); Online payment portal security; Payment plan management; Billing system security; Practice management system scoping; Electronic Health Record (EHR) scoping; Insurance claim processing (typically out of PCI scope if no CHD stored); Patient payment plans; Tokenization recommended; Role-based access control; Staff training (PCI DSS and HIPAA); Physical security; Quarterly ASV scans; Penetration testing (Level 1-2); Business associate agreements with payment processors; Incident response (coordinate PCI and HIPAA breach notification)
nodes.name: Healthcare Provider Accepting Cards
nodes.definition: Healthcare organizations accepting payment cards for patient payments, co-pays, deductibles, and medical services. Subject to both PCI DSS and HIPAA requirements creating complex compliance environment.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); HIPAA Security Rule (mandatory); HIPAA Privacy Rule; HITECH Act; ISO 27001 (recommended); State healthcare privacy laws; Healthcare industry security frameworks; GDPR (if EU patients); CCPA (if California); Payment brand requirements; CMS regulations; Healthcare accreditation standards

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Educational institution accepting payment cards for institutional services, tuition, fees, or products. Subject to all PCI DSS requirements with considerations for multiple payment acceptance points (admissions, bursar, bookstore, dining, athletics, parking), student information system integration, payment plan management, and large seasonal transaction volumes. Compliance level typically Level 2-3 for large universities.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); Often requires comprehensive assessment due to distributed payment acceptance
nodes.compliance_level: Varies (Level 1-4 based on transaction volume); Large universities often Level 1-2
nodes.transaction_threshold: Compliance level determined by annual transaction volume across all campus departments
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements across all departments; Centralized payment security policy; Decentralized payment acceptance point security; Student information system (SIS) scoping; Bursar office security; Bookstore POS security; Dining services payment systems; Athletic ticket sales; Parking payment systems; Online payment portals; Payment plan management; Network segmentation; Departmental security responsibility matrix; Faculty/staff training; Student worker training; Third-party vendor management (payment processors); Campus-wide network security; Wireless network security; Physical security; Quarterly ASV scans; Penetration testing; Incident response coordination; Payment Card Acceptance Policy
nodes.name: Educational Institution
