nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Non-profit organization accepting payment cards for donations, memberships, event registrations, or other contributions. Subject to identical PCI DSS requirements as for-profit merchants with compliance level determined by transaction volume. Often face compliance challenges due to limited budgets, volunteer staff, and resource constraints. No exemptions from PCI DSS based on non-profit status.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); Most complete SAQ A, A-EP, or C depending on processing method
nodes.compliance_level: Varies (Level 1-4 based on transaction volume); Most non-profits Level 3-4
nodes.transaction_threshold: Compliance level determined by annual transaction volume (see Level 1-4 thresholds)
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements (no non-profit exemptions); Donation page security (if accepting online donations); Payment processor selection (consider hosted solutions to reduce scope); Recurring donation management; Event registration security; Membership management system security; Volunteer access controls; Outsourcing security functions (cost-effective approach); Third-party fundraising platform security; Payment terminal security; Donor data protection; Tokenization recommended; Training for staff and volunteers; Written security policies; Quarterly ASV scans; Incident response; Budget allocation for security; Grant funding for compliance; Third-party compliance services
nodes.name: Non-Profit Organization
nodes.definition: Non-profit organizations, charities, foundations, religious organizations, and NGOs accepting payment card donations, membership fees, event registrations, or fundraising contributions. Often have limited IT resources and security expertise creating compliance challenges. Subject to full PCI DSS requirements regardless of non-profit status.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); GDPR (if EU donors); CCPA (if California); Charitable solicitation regulations; State non-profit regulations; IRS regulations (tax-deductible donations); Non-profit governance standards; Payment brand requirements; Regional data protection laws; Fundraising regulations

Subject to all PCI DSS requirements PLUS additional government security frameworks (FISMA, NIST, FedRAMP, etc.). Must coordinate PCI DSS compliance with government IT security requirements creating complex compliance environment. Compliance level based on transaction volume; large agencies often Level 1-2.
nodes.assessment_type: Varies by level: QSA audit (Level 1-2) or SAQ (Level 3-4); Often requires QSA due to complexity and government requirements

nodes.name: Government Agency
nodes.definition: Federal, state, local, or international government entities accepting payment cards for taxes, fees, fines, permits, licenses, utility payments, or government services. Subject to PCI DSS plus additional government security requirements (NIST, FedRAMP, FISMA). Often process high volumes with sensitive citizen data requiring enhanced security controls.

nodes.pci_dss_definition: Per PCI DSS: Platform operator facilitating payment card transactions between multiple parties (buyers, sellers, service providers). May function as merchant of record, payment facilitator, or intermediary depending on payment model. Responsible for platform security, sub-merchant/seller compliance (if applicable), payment processing security, and protection of cardholder data. Compliance level typically Level 1 due to volume and complexity.
nodes.assessment_type: Annual Onsite Assessment by QSA (typically required); Report on Compliance; Quarterly ASV scans; Annual penetration testing

nodes.transaction_threshold: Typically exceeds 6 million transactions/year when aggregating all platform transactions
nodes.compliance_requirements: All 12 PCI DSS requirements for platform infrastructure; Platform application security (web application firewall, secure coding); API security (buyer/seller APIs); Payment gateway integration security; Tokenization (recommended); Sub-merchant compliance program (if payment facilitator model); Seller onboarding security validation; Know Your Customer (KYC) for sellers; Transaction monitoring and fraud detection; Split payment security (if revenue sharing); Multi-currency payment security; Chargeback management; Dispute resolution system security; Marketplace-specific fraud patterns; Identity verification; Seller agreement security clauses; Network segmentation; Logging and monitoring; Incident response; Quarterly ASV scans; Annual penetration testing; Third-party integration security (shipping, logistics, etc.)
nodes.name: Marketplace / Platform Operator
nodes.definition: Digital marketplace platforms connecting buyers and sellers, facilitating payments between parties. Includes e-commerce marketplaces, sharing economy platforms, freelance platforms, crowdfunding platforms, and multi-vendor shopping platforms. Complex compliance environment as platform may act as merchant, facilitator, or payment intermediary.
nodes.applicable_standards: PCI DSS v4.0.1 (mandatory); ISO 27001; SOC 2 Type II; Payment facilitator regulations (if applicable); E-commerce regulations; GDPR; CCPA; Consumer protection laws; Marketplace-specific regulations; Anti-Money Laundering (AML); Know Your Customer (KYC); Regional e-commerce laws; Payment brand requirements; Platform security standards

nodes.name: Primary Account Number
nodes.definition: 15 or 16-digit unique identifier for a payment card account assigned by the card issuer.
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.5: Render PAN Unreadable
nodes.official_pci_description: The Primary Account Number (PAN) is the principal account number identifying the cardholder account. Per PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.5, PANs must be rendered unreadable at all points where stored through one of four methods: (1) encryption of stored PAN using strong cryptography; (2) tokenization of PAN; (3) truncation of PAN; (4) hash-based mechanism using strong cryptography. PANs must be masked in display (show first 6 and last 4 digits only).

nodes.name: Cardholder Name
nodes.definition: The full name of the individual to whom the payment card is issued, as printed on the card.
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3: Protect Stored Cardholder Data
nodes.official_pci_description: Cardholder name is account data constituting Cardholder Data (CHD) per PCI DSS v4.0.1. Must be protected per Requirement 3 with appropriate encryption when stored. Subject to access restrictions (Requirement 7) and audit logging (Requirement 10). Must be deleted according to documented data retention policies. Retention period must be based on business need with documented justification.

nodes.name: Card Expiration Date
nodes.definition: The month and year (MM/YY format) indicating when the payment card expires and is no longer valid for transactions.
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3: Protect Stored Cardholder Data
nodes.official_pci_description: Card expiration date is account data constituting Cardholder Data (CHD) per PCI DSS v4.0.1. Must be protected per Requirement 3 if stored. Subject to data minimization principle - storage only if business justified. Must be encrypted if stored. Subject to documented retention policies with secure deletion upon retention period expiration.

nodes.name: Service Code
nodes.definition: Three-digit code encoded on the magnetic stripe (or embedded in chip) that provides information about card usage limitations and transaction requirements. Also called CVC1 (Card Verification Code 1).
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3: Protect Stored Cardholder Data
nodes.official_pci_description: Service Code is account data constituting Cardholder Data (CHD) per PCI DSS v4.0.1. Provides information about cardholder authorization and usage limitations. Must be protected per Requirement 3 if stored. Subject to encryption requirement (AES-256 minimum) if retained. Storage justified only by business need. Retention period documented with secure deletion.

nodes.deletion_requirement: MUST DELETE immediately after transaction authorization
nodes.data_element: Full Track Data / Magnetic Stripe Data
nodes.name: Full Track Data
nodes.definition: Complete data from the magnetic stripe or chip equivalent, including all encoded information (Track 1 and Track 2) used during transaction authorization.
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.2: Sensitive Authentication Data Cannot Be Stored After Authorization
nodes.official_pci_description: Sensitive Authentication Data (SAD) per PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.2. Full track data contains all magnetic stripe data encoded on the card. PCI DSS v4.0.1 explicitly prohibits storage of SAD after transaction authorization under ANY circumstances, including encrypted form. Only exception: Card issuers with documented, legitimate business need (per Requirement 3.3). Violation of this requirement is critical compliance failure.

nodes.deletion_requirement: MUST DELETE immediately after transaction authorization
nodes.name: Card Verification Code
nodes.definition: 3 or 4-digit security code on card (varies by card brand) used to verify cardholder identity during transactions. Visa: CVV2 (back); Mastercard: CVC2 (back); Amex: CID (front).
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.2: Sensitive Authentication Data Cannot Be Stored After Authorization
nodes.official_pci_description: Sensitive Authentication Data (SAD) per PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.2. Card Verification Code (CVV, CVV2, CVC2, CID depending on brand) is authentication credential that cannot be stored after authorization. Absolute prohibition - no exceptions except issuers with documented need. Even encrypted storage is violation. Must be deleted in real-time after authorization is obtained. Storage violates PCI DSS Requirement 3.2.

nodes.deletion_requirement: MUST DELETE immediately after transaction authorization
nodes.name: Personal Identification Number
nodes.definition: Personal Identification Number (PIN) or PIN Block used for cardholder authentication, particularly for ATM and debit transactions. PIN Block is encrypted PIN for transmission.
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.2 & 3.3: SAD Cannot Be Stored
nodes.official_pci_description: Sensitive Authentication Data (SAD) per PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirements 3.2 and 3.3. PIN and PIN block data cannot be stored after transaction authorization under normal circumstances. Limited exception only for card issuers with explicit, documented business justification (Requirement 3.3). Storage of PIN/PIN blocks by merchants or service providers violates requirement. Must be deleted immediately upon authorization completion.

nodes.name: Card Activation Key
nodes.definition: Cryptographic key used by card issuers and processors to activate and personalize newly issued payment cards.
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.2: Sensitive Authentication Data Cannot Be Stored
nodes.official_pci_description: Sensitive Authentication Data (SAD) per PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 3.2. Card Activation Keys are cryptographic credentials used in card activation and personalization process. Cannot be stored after transaction/use completion. Absolute prohibition on storage. Used only by card issuers and payment processors. Must be deleted upon completion of activation process.

nodes.storage_allowed: Depends on element (CHD: YES, SAD: NO post-auth)
nodes.encryption_required: Depends on element (CHD: YES, SAD: N/A)
nodes.deletion_requirement: Depends on element per retention policy
nodes.name: Account Data (Combined)
nodes.definition: Collective term for both Cardholder Data (CHD) and Sensitive Authentication Data (SAD) together. Refers to any data that could be used fraudulently to obtain, authorize, or use payment cards.
nodes.official_pci_description: Account Data is defined in PCI DSS v4.0.1 as either Cardholder Data or Sensitive Authentication Data. Cardholder Data (allowed with encryption): PAN, cardholder name, expiration date, service code. Sensitive Authentication Data (prohibited post-authorization): Full track data, CVV/CVV2/CVC2/CID, PIN/PIN blocks, CAK. Organizations must maintain policies defining what account data is stored, where, duration, and how it is destroyed. Account data inventory required.

nodes.name: Cardholder Data in Transit
nodes.definition: Payment card information being transmitted between systems, networks, or organizations during payment processing authorization and settlement.
nodes.official_regulation_reference: PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 4: Protect Cardholder Data with Strong Cryptography During Transmission
nodes.official_pci_description: Cardholder Data in transit must be protected per PCI DSS v4.0.1 Requirement 4. All CHD transmitted over public networks must be encrypted using strong cryptography (TLS 1.2 or higher minimum). Point-to-Point Encryption (P2PE) may be used for in-store transactions. End-to-end encryption protects CHD from point of entry through processing. Encryption keys must be protected. No fallback to weak protocols allowed.

nodes.description: Examine network diagrams to verify they identify all connections between the CDE and other networks
Examine data retention and disposal policies and procedures to verify that data is only retained for as long as necessary.
Interview responsible personnel to verify that data retention and disposal policies are defined and understood.
Examine system configurations or display settings to verify that PAN is masked when displayed.
Observe screens displaying PAN to verify that only the first six and last four digits are displayed.
Examine the targeted risk analysis (TRA) to verify that the frequency of periodic malware scans is defined.
Examine policies and procedures to verify processes are defined to detect and protect personnel against phishing attacks.
Observe security controls to verify that automated mechanisms are in place to detect and protect personnel against phishing.
Examine the inventory of bespoke and custom software to verify it is maintained and includes all custom software.
Examine configurations and script authorization records to verify a method is implemented to confirm each payment page script is authorized.
Examine system configuration settings to verify that passwords are required to be a minimum length of 12 characters and contain both numeric and alphabetic characters.
Examine system configuration settings to verify that individuals cannot submit a new password that is the same as any of the last four passwords used.
Examine configurations and scripts for application and system accounts to verify passwords/passphrases are protected against misuse.
Examine configuration settings to verify a change- and tamper-detection mechanism is deployed for payment pages.
Verify via observation or testing that the mechanism alerts personnel to unauthorized modifications of HTTP headers or page content.
Examine documentation to verify that PCI DSS scope is confirmed at least once every 12 months.
Interview responsible personnel to verify that the scope confirmation is accurate and includes all flows and locations of cardholder data.
Examine the incident response plan to verify it includes response procedures for alerts from change-detection mechanisms and detection of unencrypted PAN.
